# k9x.sh

A simple shell function to enhance your `k9s` experience. It interactively prompts you to select a `kubeconfig` file and a Kubernetes context using `fzf` and `kubectx`, then opens `k9s` with your selections. This streamlines access to your Kubernetes clusters.

## Prerequisites

Before using `k9x`, ensure you have the following tools installed:

-   **[kubectx](https://github.com/ahmetb/kubectx)**: A faster way to switch between clusters and namespaces in `kubectl`.
-   **[fzf](https://github.com/junegunn/fzf?tab=readme-ov-file#using-homebrew)**: A command-line fuzzy finder.

You can typically install these using your system's package manager (e.g., Homebrew on macOS, `apt` on Debian/Ubuntu, `yum` on CentOS/RHEL).

## Installation

To add the `k9x` function to your shell, append the following code to your shell's configuration file (e.g., `~/.bashrc` for Bash or `~/.zshrc` for Zsh):

```bash
k9x() {
  local kubeconfig_file
  local context

  # List kubeconfig files and select one using fzf
  # Assumes kubeconfig files are directly in ~/.kube/
  kubeconfig_file=$(ls -p ~/.kube | grep -v / | fzf --prompt="Select kubeconfig > ")
  [[ -z "$kubeconfig_file" ]] && return 1

  # For the selected kubeconfig, choose a context
  context=$(KUBECONFIG="$HOME/.kube/$kubeconfig_file" kubectx | fzf --prompt="Select context > ")
  [[ -z "$context" ]] && return 1
  
  # Open k9s with the selected kubeconfig and context
  k9s --splashless -A -c pod --kubeconfig "$HOME/.kube/$kubeconfig_file" --context "$context"
}
```

After adding the function, reload your shell configuration:

```bash
source ~/.zshrc # Or source ~/.bashrc for Bash users
```

## Usage

Simply run `k9x` in your terminal:

```bash
k9x
```

The function will guide you through selecting your `kubeconfig` and context.

## Tips

-   If you exit `k9s` using `:q`, it will save your session state, allowing you to return to where you left off. Using `Ctrl+C` will not save the session.
-   Ensure your `kubeconfig` files are located directly in `~/.kube/` for the script to find them.